==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: groan
<hw>groan</hw> <pr>(gr⟦omac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Groaned</conjf> <pr>(gr⟦omac⟧nd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr.
& vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Groaning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>gronen</ets>, <ets>granen</ets>, <ets>granien</ets>, AS.
<ets>gr⟦amac⟧nian</ets>, fr. the root of grennian to grin. ⟦root⟧35. See
<er>2d Grin</er>, and cf. <er>Grunt</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
give forth a low, moaning sound in breathing; to utter a groan, as in
pain, in sorrow, or in derision; to moan.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For we . . . do <qex>groan</qex>, being burdened.</q> <rj><qau>2
Cor. v. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He heard the <qex>groaning</qex> of the oak.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott. </qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To strive after earnestly, as with groans.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nothing but holy, pure, and clear,⟦br⟧
Or that which <ex>groaneth</ex> to be so.</q>
<rj><qau>Herbert.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Groan</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Groan
<hw>Groan</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To affect by groans.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Groan</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Groan
<hw>Groan</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A low, moaning sound; usually, a
deep, mournful sound uttered in pain or great distress; sometimes, an
expression of strong disapprobation; <as>as, the remark was received
with <ex>groans</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such <qex>groans</qex> of roaring wind and rain.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wretched animal heaved forth such <qex>groans</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Groanful</ent>⟦br⟧
